   "source": [
    "# Kernels"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8098c6d9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this chapter we will be explaining what kernels are, how they affect your models, and how you can create them.\n",
    "\n",
    "These are the imports we will be using below:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "439e940a",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:38:54.605508Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:38:54.605320Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:38:57.375385Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:38:57.374819Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from typing import Optional, Sequence\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from matplotlib.axes import Axes\n",
    "\n",
    "import gpflow"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cab31d4e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## What is a Kernel?\n",
    "\n",
    "Remember how we assume that our data is generated by:\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "Y_i = f(X_i) + \\varepsilon_i \\,, \\quad \\varepsilon_i \\sim \\mathcal{N}(0, \\sigma^2).\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "And in [Basic Usage](basic_usage.html) we defined our model as:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "476df14d",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:38:57.377734Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:38:57.377467Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:38:57.421170Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:38:57.420632Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.RBF(),\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9728ba9c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The `kernel` defines what kind of shapes $f$ can take.\n",
    "\n",
    "Technically, a kernel is a function that takes $X$ values and returns a $N \\times N$ covariance matrix telling us how those $X$ coordinates relate to each other. However, for many users it may be more useful to develop an intuitive understanding of how the different kernels behave than to study the maths.\n",
    "\n",
    "A kernel is sometimes also known as a covariance function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a52a7c3d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Visualising a Kernel\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the function we will use to visualise some kernels below:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "3e277d80",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:38:57.423501Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:38:57.423332Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:38:57.431879Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:38:57.431488Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def _plot_samples(\n",
    "    ax: Axes, kernels: Sequence[gpflow.kernels.Kernel], labels: Sequence[Optional[str]]\n",
    ") -> None:\n",
    "    X = np.zeros((0, 1))\n",
    "    Y = np.zeros((0, 1))\n",
    "    n_kernels = len(kernels)\n",
    "    legend = n_kernels > 1\n",
    "    n_samples = 3 if len(kernels) == 1 else 1\n",
    "    for kernel, label in zip(kernels, labels):\n",
    "        model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "            (X, Y),\n",
    "            kernel=kernel,\n",
    "        )\n",
    "        Xplot = np.linspace(-0.1, 1.1, 100)[:, None]\n",
    "        fs = model.predict_f_samples(Xplot, n_samples)\n",
    "        if not legend:\n",
    "            label = None\n",
    "        ax.plot(Xplot, fs[:, :, 0].numpy().T, label=label)\n",
    "    if legend:\n",
    "        ax.legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def _plot_predictions(\n",
    "    ax: Axes, kernels: Sequence[gpflow.kernels.Kernel], labels: Sequence[Optional[str]]\n",
    ") -> None:\n",
    "    X = np.array([[0.0], [0.1], [1.0]])\n",
    "    Y = np.array([[0.1], [0.0], [1.0]])\n",
    "    n_kernels = len(kernels)\n",
    "    legend = n_kernels > 1\n",
    "    for kernel, label in zip(kernels, labels):\n",
    "        model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "            (X, Y),\n",
    "            kernel=kernel,\n",
    "            noise_variance=1e-3,\n",
    "        )\n",
    "        gpflow.set_trainable(model.likelihood, False)\n",
    "        opt = gpflow.optimizers.Scipy()\n",
    "        opt.minimize(\n",
    "            model.training_loss, model.trainable_variables, options=dict(maxiter=100)\n",
    "        )\n",
    "\n",
    "        Xplot = np.linspace(-0.1, 1.1, 100)[:, None]\n",
    "\n",
    "        f_mean, f_var = model.predict_f(Xplot, full_cov=False)\n",
    "        f_lower = f_mean - 1.96 * np.sqrt(f_var)\n",
    "        f_upper = f_mean + 1.96 * np.sqrt(f_var)\n",
    "\n",
    "        if not legend:\n",
    "            label = None\n",
    "\n",
    "        ax.plot(X, Y, \"kx\", mew=2, label=\"input data\")\n",
    "        (mean_line,) = ax.plot(Xplot, f_mean, \"-\", label=label)\n",
    "        color = mean_line.get_color()\n",
    "        ax.plot(Xplot, f_lower, \"--\", color=color)\n",
    "        ax.plot(Xplot, f_upper, \"--\", color=color)\n",
    "        ax.fill_between(\n",
    "            Xplot[:, 0], f_lower[:, 0], f_upper[:, 0], color=color, alpha=0.1\n",
    "        )\n",
    "\n",
    "    if legend:\n",
    "        ax.legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_kernels(\n",
    "    kernels: Sequence[gpflow.kernels.Kernel],\n",
    "    labels: Optional[Sequence[Optional[str]]] = None,\n",
    ") -> None:\n",
    "    if labels is None:\n",
    "        labels = [k.__class__.__name__ for k in kernels]\n",
    "\n",
    "    fig, (samples_ax, prediction_ax) = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)\n",
    "    _plot_samples(samples_ax, kernels, labels)\n",
    "    _plot_predictions(prediction_ax, kernels, labels)"
   ]
  },
